The N2 adsorption–desorption isotherms and pore size distributions of the P25, TNSs, @Gd-C-0-TNSs (@=0.1%, 0.25%, 0.5%, 1.0%, 1.5%, and 2.0%) and 0.5%Gd-C-X-TNSs (X=0.0, 1.0, 2.0, 3.0, 6.0, and 10.0) are measured to analyze their porous properties. Fig. S2 shows that the N2 adsorption–desorption isotherms of the TNSs belong to a typical Type IV sorption behavior with a large Type-H3 hysteresis hoop, which represents the mesoporous structure according to the classification of IUPAC, with the mesopores mainly originating from the interspaces of the aggregated nanosheets [42]. The hysteresis hoops are also observed in the @Gd-C-0-TNS and 0.5%Gd-C-X-TNS samples and show a lower absorption than bare TNSs at a high range of relative pressures (0.60<P/P0
                        <0.99), indicating a decrease in the mesopores. In addition, the @Gd-C-0-TNS and 0.5%Gd-C-X-TNS samples exhibit an average pore size with a narrow distribution, which is slightly lower than that of pure TNSs, probably because of the dispersion of smaller Gd2O3 nanoparticles (or carbon dots) into the pores of the TNSs. These results were also confirmed by the decreasing tendency of SBET from 349.25m2/g for the TNSs to 241.72m2/g for the 0.5%Gd-C-10-TNSs (Table 1
                        ). These results suggest that the ion-exchange in the hydrothermal process (or the deposition process of CDs) allows the Gd2O3 nanoparticles (or carbon dots) to enter into the interspaces of the aggregated nanosheets and block the mesopores among them. Thus, SBET and the pore volume of the TNSs decrease.

Further, to analyze the synergistic photocatalytic Cr(VI) and RhB decontamination using 0.5%Gd-C-3-TNSs, the simultaneous photocatalytic removal of RhB and Cr(VI) under visible light irradiation was conducted. The degradation profiles of RhB when its initial concentration was 20ppm in the absence and presence of Cr(VI) at 50ppm are shown in Fig. 7
                           a. The addition of Cr(VI) effectively increased the degradation rate of RhB. During the first 50min, the presence of Cr(VI) led to a kinetic constant that was more than 1.391-fold that of isolated RhB. In addition, the degradation efficiency for RhB was found to increase because of the presence of Cr(VI). The improvement in the rate and extent of RhB degradation demonstrated that Cr(VI) is an efficient scavenger of photo-generated electrons. On the other hand, no considerable reaction between RhB and Cr(VI) was observed under homogeneous conditions in the absence of the photocatalyst. Because of the existence of another electron acceptor oxygen with a drastic reduction in the amount of Cr(VI), after irradiation for 50min, the rate of RhB degradation decreased in the presence of Cr(VI). In a similar way, an increase in removal rate for Cr(VI) can be shown by the presence of RhB (Fig. 7b). The removal efficiency for Cr(VI) increased in the presence of RhB, which was found to be 2.42-times higher than that in its absence (Table 4
                           ).
